         <abstract>
            <p>The study investigates the validity of the efficient markets version of purchasing power parity for a group of Latin American black market currencies. Two testable implications of the efficient market hypothesis are examined, as suggested by Roll [20]. The appropriate tests are conducted for each country individually and for all countries simultaneously. The results lend support to the efficient markets hypothesis, an interesting finding given the perceived characteristics of the currencies examined.</p>
         </abstract>
